414.text:
you see, a dog growls when it's angry,
and wags its tail when it's pleased. Now _I_ growl when I'm pleased,
and wag my tail when I'm angry. Therefore I'm mad.

417.text:
Do you play croquet with the
Queen to-day?

418.text: I should like it very much,

419.text:
but I haven't been invited
yet.

421.text: By-the-bye, what became of the baby?

426.text:
the March Hare will be much the most interesting, and
perhaps as this is May it won't be raving mad--at least not so mad as it
was in March.

427.text: Did you say pig, or fig?

429.text:
and I wish you wouldn't keep appearing
and vanishing so suddenly: you make one quite giddy.

431.text: Well! I've often seen a cat without a grin,

432.text:
but a
grin without a cat! It's the most curious thing I ever saw in my life!

433.text:
Suppose it should be raving mad after all!
I almost wish I'd gone to see the Hatter instead!
